      <intermediateExchange id="8ed27e62-b7f1-5baa-8104-cafc925ca9dc" unitId="86bbe475-8a8f-44d8-914c-e398787e7121" amount="0.000118957399855596" intermediateExchangeId="75168394-3da2-467a-90a1-285836ccd00d" activityLinkId="ce3b617c-7d3c-5df2-9a64-0e9554f11941">
        <name xml:lang="en">fertilising, by broadcaster</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">ha</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">2.00 ha/ha (1.19E-4 ha/kg Sweet Corn) fertilising, by broadcaster
Average application rates for mineral fertilisers (NPKS) on Sweet Corn in Minnesota are: 1.70 N applications on 97.0% of cropped area, 1.10 P applications on 69.0% of cropped area, 1.00 K applications on 59.0% of cropped area, and 1.10 S applications on 26.0% of cropped area (NPKS data from 2018). Applications of N are split between anhydrous ammonia and other N, because they are applied differently, with different equipment Other than anhydrous ammonia, most NPK(S) fertilisers are applied together via broadcast application.
Anhydrous ammonia application (knifing/injection) is calculated as market share of N that is anhydrous ammonia * total N applications (=0.42). Other N application is then total USDA N applications less applications of anhydrous ammonia (=1.28). The market share of N that is anhydrous ammonia is calculated from fertiliser market group shares crossed with meeting NPKS nutrient demand (here, 24.78%). Thus, the dataset includes 0.41 anhydrous ammonia applications via injection (0.42 * 97.0% of crop area with applied N) and 1.24 other N applications via broadcast (1.28 * 97.0%). Since the number of passes for N application after removing the anhydrous ammonia share is greater than the maximum number of passes reported for the other nutrients, this dataset assumes that any other fertiliser applications are reflected under that pass and the total fertiliser broadcast fertiliser passes are thus 1.24.

Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance unless otherwise noted.  (UWM Extension 2014, Hanna, Mark 2016, Schuler and Frank 1998, Lattz and Schnitkey 2021b).  Operations are matched to equipment type and where multiple options are available, the share of each is determined from guidance and annual farmer survey data (Custom Rate Summaries) for contracted operations/equipment. Where an operation applies only to a portion of the harvested area, the number of passes has been scaled by the % of harvested area to which it applies (e.g., manure spreading or insecticide) as indicated by USDA statistics (applications) or USDA reports (manure use) or as otherwise indicated in enterprise crop budgets.
Source(s): 
USDA NASS (2022d) Applications - fertilizers and pesticides - number, amount, - Sweet Corn- 2000-2021. US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Agricultural Statistics Service. https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov (direct query: https://quickstats.nass.usda.gov/results/13FC0C89-E211-3D0B-A9C5-BCFC35728512); UWM Extension (2014) Pricing, Contracts &amp; Budgets. Cooperative Extension Service, University of Wisconsin-Madison. https://farms.extension.wisc.edu/article-topic/pricing-and-contracts/, Hanna, Mark (2016) Estimating the Field Capacity of Farm Machines. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/pdf/a3-24.pdf, Schuler and Frank (1998) A3510 Estimating Agricultural Field Machinery Costs. University of Wisconsin-Extension. https://learningstore.uwex.edu/Assets/pdfs/A3510.pdf, Lattz and Schnitkey (2021b) Machinery Cost Estimates: Field Operations. Department of Agricultural and Consumer Economics, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. https://farmdoc.illinois.edu/assets/management/machinery-costs/field_operations.pdf</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="0.000118957399855596" mu="-9.036745113351214" variance="0.0006" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.0206"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="4" completeness="4" temporalCorrelation="3" geographicalCorrelation="1" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="3"/>
        </uncertainty>
