      <intermediateExchange id="0f033069-9416-526f-b95d-8a9cb01578bb" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="5.94786999277979E-05" intermediateExchangeId="dbb096cb-7d2c-56f1-8c42-6b8da47ddb6b" activityLinkId="f731652d-64fc-5895-b8ad-baaf5413f763">
        <name xml:lang="en">harvesting, use of harvesting cart</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">5.95E-5 ha/kg harvesting, use of harvesting cart (1. effective pass(es) per year). 
This dataset includes use of a harvesting cart in association with manual harvest for collection of filled crates during harvest.The 2014 enterprise crop budget (the most recent detailed budget available for WI) uses manual harvest and includes 30.5 hours manual labor for that harvest, persumably using harvest cart or truck. Other practices are based on annual guidance for commercial vegetable production (Colquhoun, J.B et al 2022).  State specific guidance for Minessota is not available. Field operations are assumed as Wisconsin.Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance unless otherwise noted. Operations are matched to equipment type and where multiple options are available, the share of each is determined from guidance and annual farmer survey data (Custom Rate Summaries) for contracted operations/equipment. Field cultivation and tillage operations are specific to the tillage regime used. Seed establishment and weed control for sweet corn generally require tillage (EPA 2022; IPM 2003, IPM 1997), so this dataset reflects sweet corn production using conventional tillage practices (0% reduced till, 100% conventional tillage, and 0% no till, ). Used for manual harvesting.
Sources:
UWM Extension 2014, Hanna, Mark 2016, Schuler and Frank 1998, Lattz and Schnitkey 2021b; UWM Extension (2014) Pricing, Contracts &amp; Budgets. Cooperative Extension Service, University of Wisconsin-Madison. https://farms.extension.wisc.edu/article-topic/pricing-and-contracts/, Hanna, Mark (2016) Estimating the Field Capacity of Farm Machines. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://www.extension.iastate.edu/agdm/crops/pdf/a3-24.pdf, Schuler and Frank (1998) A3510 Estimating Agricultural Field Machinery Costs. University of Wisconsin-Extension. https://learningstore.uwex.edu/Assets/pdfs/A3510.pdf, Lattz and Schnitkey (2021b) Machinery Cost Estimates: Field Operations. Department of Agricultural and Consumer Economics, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. https://farmdoc.illinois.edu/assets/management/machinery-costs/field_operations.pdf; EPA (2022) Assessment of the Benefits of Atrazine and the Impacts of Potential Mitigation for Field Corn, Sweet Corn, Sorghum, and Sugarcane; PC Code (080803). (MEMORANDUM).US Environmental Protection Agency. https://downloads.regulations.gov/EPA-HQ-OPP-2013-0266-1624/content.pdf ; IPM center (2003) Crop Profile for Sweet Corn in the North Central United States. Southern Integrated Pest Management Center.Southern Integrated Pest Management Center. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/us-ncr-sweetcorn.pdf ; IPM center (1997) Crop Profile for Corn (Sweet) in Maryland. Southern Integrated Pest Management Center. https://ipmdata.ipmcenters.org/documents/cropprofiles/MDcorn-sweet.pdf</comment>
