      <intermediateExchange id="69def57b-eb4b-5ee7-8d16-f5b460d6702a" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="001317-65-3" amount="0.00626343785070198" intermediateExchangeId="64cea105-f89a-4f95-ae44-84ff904a28fc" activityLinkId="2659aacd-df83-5c93-9180-56a0c05ff487">
        <name xml:lang="en">limestone, crushed, washed</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Application of limestone to raise soil pH, 105.31 kg/ha (6.26E-3 kg/kg Sweet Corn), calculated as the (mass of lime applied to treated acres (2 t/treated ha)) * fraction of crop area treated with lime (14.9%, from soil pH data from Bruulsema T and Jones J D 2021) / (7  years between applications, based on Fernández F G and Hoeft R G  2012a). 
Lime is applied to all soils with pH below 6 based on expert guidance (Sawyer JE 2020). Cropped area needing liming is determined from  distribution of soil pH sampling results reported in the 2020 Soil Test Summary (Bruulsema and Jones 2021). The share of acidic soils is likely overestimated as more more frequent testing is to be expected on soils having needed lime and thus low pH soils are likely to be more represented amongst the collected samples. (Mallarino A P, Pagani A, Sawyer J E 2011; Fernández F G and Hoeft R G  2012; Bly A and Gelderman R 2019; Shaver T M 2014) The increase in pH with lime application remains dominant through at least 4 years from application and guidance suggests 4 to 10 years beween applications (Fernández F G and Hoeft R G  2012).
Sources: 
Bruulsema T and Jones J D (2021) Soil Test Summary 2020. Foundation for Agronomic Research and Plant Nutrition Canada present this 2020 summary of soil test levels in North America. Foundation for Agronomic Research, Plant Nutrition Canada. https://soiltest.tfi.org/about/about_soil_test_summaryaccessed August 30, 2021; Kaiser and Ronen (2018) Lime needs in Minnesota (website). University of Minnesota Extension. https://extension.umn.edu/liming/lime-needs-minnesotaaccessed August 30, 2021; Mamo, M, Wortmann, CS, Shaipro, CA (2015) Lime Use for Soil Acidity Management. University of Nebraska–Lincoln Extension, Institute of Agriculture and Natural Resources. https://extensionpublications.unl.edu/assets/pdf/g1504.pdfaccessed August 30, 2021; Fernández F G and Hoeft R G  (2012a) Managing Soil pH and Crop Nutrients. Chapter 8 in the Illinois Agronomy Handbook.Crop Science Extension &amp; Outreach, University of Illinois . http://extension.cropsciences.illinois.edu/handbook/pdfs/chapter08.pdf; Shaver T M (2014) Nutrient Management for Agronomic Crops in Nebraska (rev Dec 2014). The University of Nebraska Institute of Agriculture and Natural Resources. https://extensionpublications.unl.edu/assets/pdf/ec155.pdfaccessed August 30, 2021; Bly A and Gelderman R (2019) Chapter: 25 Liming South Dakota Soils . SDSU Extension . https://extension.sdstate.edu/sites/default/files/2019-09/S-0003-25-Corn.pdf; Mallarino A P, Pagani A, Sawyer J E (2011) Corn and soybean response to soil pH level and liming. Paper presented at the 2011 Integrated Crop Management Conference. Iowa State University.Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/128983337.pdfaccessed November 17, 2021</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="0.00626343785070198" mu="-5.073026067184435" variance="0.12" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.1381"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="4" completeness="2" temporalCorrelation="3" geographicalCorrelation="1" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="3"/>
