      <intermediateExchange id="baabbe5d-946e-57bc-950f-8001f84a91ea" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="0.000729679397979882" intermediateExchangeId="cff23b42-5fa8-471b-b6fb-8a2cca249ca8" activityLinkId="1c608e58-eca0-5d8f-9e7a-424184718473">
        <name xml:lang="en">maize seed, for sowing</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Each planted hectare uses 12.27 kg seed (7.3E-4 kg/kg Sweet Corn). This value is calculated from a seeding rate of 76,603 seeds/ha (Licht M, Parvej M R, Baum M 2019, Licht M 2020) and an average seed count of 6,244 seeds/kg (averaged from commercial listings of F1 (SH2 and se-se) seeds, https://www.ufseeds.com/vegetables/corn/supersweet-sh2-corn, https://lacrosseseed.com/product-information/forage-tech-sheets/tech-sheets-alfalfa-5). While genetically engineered sweet (fresh) corn seed is available, the share of sweet (fresh) corn grown from genetically engineered seed is not compiled; it is estimated that between 75 and 90% of North American sweet corn is conventional (USDA 2018b). Seeding rates are based on state average guidance, not specifically for GE or conventional seed.  Germination and stand losses are accounted for in the seeding rate.The uncertainty parameters are calculated from the uncertainty on the range of seed sizes (seed counts per kg), the yield variation, and the variability in seed-to-stand ratios.  Sources:
Lindsey AJ, Thomison PR, Nafziger ED  (2018) Estimated Return-to-Seed of Variable vs. Uniform Corn Seeding Rates. Crop Ecophysiology and Agronomy, Ohio State University; Corn Cropping Systems Extension, Ohio State University; Crop Sciences, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. https://ohioline.osu.edu/factsheet/agf-520, USDA NASS. (2020). Crops/Stocks Survey (or Agricultural Survey) for the years 2000-20 - Recent Trends in GE Adoption. US Department of Agriculture (USDA). https://www.ers.usda.gov/data-products/adoption-of-genetically-engineered-crops-in-the-us/documentation/ , Mekonnen et al (2018) Water, Energy, and Carbon Footprints of Bioethanol from the U.S. and Brazil. Environ. Sci. Technol. 52:14508–14518. Mesfin M. Mekonnen, Thiago L. Romanelli, Chittaranjan Ray, Arjen Y. Hoekstra, Adam J. Liska, and Christopher M.U. Neale. https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.est.8b03359</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <normal meanValue="0.000729679397979882" variance="3.06574568322886E-08" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="3.06574568322886E-08"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="3" completeness="3" temporalCorrelation="2" geographicalCorrelation="3" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="2"/>
        </uncertainty>
