      <elementaryExchange id="264e4983-e9f9-5f0b-8235-07d7faac684a" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="007664-41-7" amount="0.000613419712073453" elementaryExchangeId="0f440cc0-0f74-446d-99d6-8ff0e97a2444" formula="H3N">
        <name xml:lang="en">Ammonia</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Ammonia volatilised from applied mineral and organic fertilisers, 10.3 kg NH3/ha (6.13E-4kg NH3/kg Sweet Corn) total, 10.3 kg NH3/ha (6.13E-4 kg NH3/kg Sweet Corn) from synthetic fertilisers, 0.0 kg NH3/ha (0.E+0 kg NH3/kg Sweet Corn) from manure. NH3 from volatilisation of mineral fertilisers is calculated using Tier 2 emission factors (temperate climate, specific fertiliser) from the European Environment Agency, EMEP/EEA 3Da1, Table3.2 (EEA 2019). NH3 from manure application is calculated with emission factors provided in EMEP/EEA 3.D.a.2.a (Animal manure applied to soils) (EEA 2019) for manure types used as (fraction TAN in total N)*(EF manure spreading per TAN) for each animal group and type. (kg NH3-N/kg N applied: ). The emissions from manure calculated here do not account for the change in N mineralization and phosphate runoff with incorporation type or time. Where impacts from manure application are expected to be significant, this should be considered as N volatilisation during and after application of manure ranges from as low as 1% N with direct injection to ~5% with immediate incorporation to 20-40% without incorporation (Sawyer J, Mallarino A P (2016) Using Manure Nutrients for Crop Production. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://store.extension.iastate.edu/product/12874and Midwast Plan Services MWPS-18, 3ed)..  NH3 from volatilisation of mineral fertilisers is calculated using Tier 2 emission factors (temperate climate, specific fertiliser) from the European Environment Agency, EMEP/EEA 3Da1, Table3.2 (EEA 2019). NH3 from manure application is calculated with emission factors provided in EMEP/EEA 3.D.a.2.a (Animal manure applied to soils) (EEA 2019) for manure types used as (fraction TAN in total N)*(EF manure spreading per TAN) for each animal group and type. (kg NH3-N/kg N applied: ). The emissions from manure calculated here do not account for the change in N mineralization and phosphate runoff with incorporation type or time. Where impacts from manure application are expected to be significant, this should be considered as N volatilisation during and after application of manure ranges from as low as 1% N with direct injection to ~5% with immediate incorporation to 20-40% without incorporation (Sawyer J, Mallarino A P (2016) Using Manure Nutrients for Crop Production. Cooperative Extension Service, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. https://store.extension.iastate.edu/product/12874and Midwast Plan Services MWPS-18, 3ed).
Sources: 
EEA (2019a) EMEP/EEA air pollutant emission inventory guidebook Part B: sectoral guidance chapters 3. Agriculture 3 D Crop production and agricultural soils. European Environment Agency. https://www.eea.europa.eu/publications/emep-eea-guidebook-2019/part-b-sectoral-guidance-chapters/4-agriculture/3-d-crop-production-and/view
EEA (2019b) EMEP/EEA air pollutant emission inventory guidebook Part B: sectoral guidance chapters 3. Agriculture 3 B Manure management. European Environment Agency. https://www.eea.europa.eu/publications/emep-eea-guidebook-2019/part-b-sectoral-guidance-chapters/4-agriculture/3-b-manure-management/view</comment>
        <uncertainty>
