    <modellingAndValidation>
      <representativeness systemModelId="290c1f85-4cc4-4fa1-b0c8-2cb7f4276dce">
        <systemModelName xml:lang="en">Allocation, cut-off by classification</systemModelName>
        <samplingProcedure xml:lang="en">Data is obtained from state, county and national statistics, agricultural extension offices, and published literature. Data for production, yields, applications of NPKS fertilisers, applications of pesticides, row width, and irrigation (if any) was obtained from the US Dept of Agriculture's National Agricultural Statistics Service and in most cases provides high-quality data spanning the dataset time period. Field operations and energy use are from enterprise crop budgets provided by local agricultural extensions offices and their farmer survey data. Literature data is used where USDA and agricultural extension guidance and data are not available.</samplingProcedure>
        <extrapolations xml:lang="en">Mineral fertiliser applications are crop and location (state and sub-state levels) specific for nutrient applied, based on survey data compiled by the USDA National Agricultural Statistics Service. Specific fertilisers are extrapolated from mineral fertiliser applications to  Specific fertilisers are extrapolated from mineral fertiliser applications to  Sweet Corn in Minnesota and market consumption in the US (IFA 2020).
 Field operations are as identified in crop- and rotation-specific enterprise crop budgets supplied by the regional agricultural extension office and matched to equipment type in the budget or crop guidance unless otherwise noted. Field cultivation and tillage operations are specific to the tillage regime used. Seed establishment and weed control for sweet corn generally require tillage (EPA 2022; IPM 2003, IPM 1997), so this dataset reflects sweet corn production using conventional tillage practices. State specific guidance for Minnessota is not available. Field operations are assumed as Wisconsin.  Operations are matched to equipment type and where multiple options are available, the share of each is determined from guidance and annual farmer survey data (Custom Rate Summaries) for contracted operations/equipment. Machine sizes (power) are approximate but based on common, recent surveys and equipment analyses (Lazarus 2020).  
 Emissions are calculated with standard methods according to ecoinvent documentation (Nemecek and Schnetzer, 2011. '01 crop production-direct field emissions natural resources' v1.2, August 2011, available at ) and the World Food LCA Database guidelines and the ecoinvent agricultural LCI tool. Soil characteristics, including pH and clay content, are extrapolated from  distribution of soil pH sampling results reported in the 2020 Soil Test Summary (Bruulsema and Jones 2021). The share of acidic soils is likely overestimated as more more frequent testing is to be expected on soils having needed lime and thus low pH soils are likely to be more represented amongst the collected samples. Drainage tile data from 2012 (reported to USDA for the 2012 agricultural census) is extrapolated as valid from that date through the rest of the time period of the dataset and the distribution of drainage is treated as homogenous for all field crops. 
 Some pesticide quantities are extrapolated. Pesticide data is sometimes withheld in the NASS database to avoid disclosing data for individual operations (denoted with "D" in the data returned for the query, indicating a non-zero but withheld value). Farmers select one or more compounds specific to their conditions, regulations, cost, and pests identified, so the full list of pesticides are not applied in any single case. Where disclosing data would allow for identification of individual operations, pesticide data is withheld in the NASS database (denoted with "D" in the data returned for the query, indicating a non-zero but withheld value). This is the case for the overwhelming majority of pesticides applied to sweet corn. Where a state-specific and substance-specific value was available in NASS, that value was used (if a value was available for both 2018 and 2020, the average of the two was used). Because farmers select one or more compounds specific to their conditions, local regulations, cost, and pests identified, the full list of pesticides are not applied in any single case and approximations are used to account for the remaining pesticides. A quantity of total insecticides/herbicides/fungicides applied is sometimes available even when many of the substances in the category are reported with a “D”. If this total is available, the amount remaining after the sum of substance-specific values is accounted for is divided equally among the substances reported with a “D”. If the sum of available values exceeds or equals the total reported, any remaining “D” substances are treated as zero and omitted. If the total used in that state is not reported, the average sweet corn country-level value for each is used for the substances reported (“D” substances). If no average US sweet corn value for the substance is available, then the value applied for US maize is used to approximate the substance to avoid undercounting since pesticide use in sweet corn cultivation is universal or nearly so. In the event that not even a value for US maize is available, the substance is omitted. If all available data across all three categories for a state are “D”, as is the case for Florida, Integrated Pest Management guidance and crop profile summaries were used to identify substances and set approximate application amounts. 
Transports are modelled with standard distances.</extrapolations>
      </representativeness>
